    <!-- ===================== SECTION THREE: Inverse Function ===================== -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDef_6">Inverse: exists if each y has unique x. f(x)↔g(x). Monotone functions have inverses. Find inverse by solving for x in terms of y.</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefQuestion_6">Does the function f(x) = 2x + 4 have an inverse?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerOne_6">True</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerTwo_6">False</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerThree_6">Neither</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_6">True</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryProperties_6">Graphs symmetric about y=x. M(x₀,y₀) ↔ N(y₀,x₀). Increasing↔increasing, decreasing↔decreasing. Used for checking inverses.</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsQuestion_6">Are the graphs of a function and its inverse symmetric about the line y = x?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerOne_6">True</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_6">False</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerThree_6">Neither</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_6">True</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExamples_6">Example 1: Find the inverse of f(x) = 2x + 4. Solve for x: y = 2x + 4 → x = (y − 4)/2. So f⁻¹(x) = (x − 4)/2. ✓
Example 2: Find the inverse of f(x) = x³. Solve: y = x³ → x = ∛y. So f⁻¹(x) = ∛x. ✓
Example 3: Verify: f(x) = 3x, f⁻¹(x) = x/3. Check: f(f⁻¹(x)) = 3·(x/3) = x. ✓</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExQuestion_6">What is the inverse of f(x) = x/2? Enter the coefficient of x in f⁻¹(x).</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_6">1/2</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_6">2</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_6">3</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_6">2</string>

